    "93176209": {
      "title": "Solid state chemical phenomena in ageing and deactivation of catalysts, in Catalyst Deactivation",
      "abstract": "Publisher Summary This chapter presents an overview of the solid state chemical reactions which have been shown to be, or which may be, operative for ageing and deactivation of catalysts. Deactivation by solid state reactions, for example, sintering or phase transformations, is necessarily a ubiquitous phenomenon. Most catalysts are metastable in the conditions of the catalytic reaction, be only because they all possess a high surface area, and hence, a high surface energy. The chapter discusses speculations on the origins of ageing and deactivation of catalysts by loss of active components. It seems advantageous to distinguish between what is because of the architecture of the catalyst and what is because of its environment\u2014namely, between characteristics inherited from the fabrication stage and behavior dictated by the working conditions. Practical ways for retarding ageing and deactivation are described."
    },
    "98009952": {
      "title": "Surface interaction model of J-alumina-supported metal oxides",
      "abstract": "An incorporation model has been proposed and used to discuss the interaction between various metal oxides and \u03b3-alumina. The dispersion capacities of various metal oxides are predicted and the surface hydroxyl group density on \u03b3-alumina estimated, based on the assumption that the (110) plane is preferentially exposed on the surface of \u03b3-alumina. These results are in good agreement with the available experimental data."
    }
  }
